Introduction¶

Problem Description¶

In this term project, it is aimed to predict the production value of the next day by using production values up to two days ago and some regressors in the energy production area with a solar panel. The regressors available for 9 different locations are as follows:

TEMP: Temperature at the provided location

REL_HUMIDITY: Relative humidity at the provided location

DSWRF: Downward shortwave radiation flux

CLOUD_LOW_LAYER: Total cloud cover data (in terms of percentage) for low-level type of clouds

In order to determine appropriate approaches and fit a valid model, output variable (production rate) is analyzed with the time series manner. After determining appropriate models, a comparison is made according to weighted mean absolute percentage errors in a certain time interval.

Summary of the Proposed Approach¶

First of all, the imported data was not in a format that could be processed, the "data.table" was brought into a format that is open to manipulation, with a single row for each date. In order to add time series components to the data, trend and seasonality components were examined (can be seen on descriptive analysis). A trend component has been added so that every hour of the day has the same trend value. Added day of the week and month variables to reduce the seasonality effect. The hour factor proved to be the biggest reason for seasonality, so it made sense to set up a different model for each hour. At this point, for the hours whose production value is generally zero, because the margin of error does not increase much and with the thought that simpler approaches can be established, the model was not established for those hours, they were discarded from the data. We preferred to use the last three months for the train phase in order to avoid high variations between seasons. In this way, clear-sky production values, which change over time, which can be considered as the capacity, would not have distorted the model. To introduce the most advanced production value available to the model, we added the lag 72 value to observe its effect. As a result of these iterations, we compared the seasonal autoregressive integrated moving average (SARIMA) model with the model we obtained and thought to work best. Here we used the auto.arima() function to find the correct p,d,q, parameters. These two models were compared in terms of WMAPE values and the model with lower error was selected. However, this model can still produce much more accurate results with further improvements, which is discussed in the conclusion phase.

Related Literature¶

According to research, many factors can affect the production efficiency of a solar panel plant. Some of these factors that either decrease or increase the production rate of a solar panel system are temperature, cloud conditions, relative humidity and radiation flux. When most of the solar energy is collected by the panels, which is generally the midday, more production output is expected. That s is why downward shortwave radiation (DSR) has a significant and positively correlated effect on the production rate. Increasing cloud conditions can be said to have a decreasing effect on the production rate, since its limit the capacity of the sun's rays to reach the panel. Temperature also has an effect on the output, because it changes the conductivity of the semiconductor, by changing the balance of charges and magnitude of the electric field. Humidity can restrict energy production from the solar panel, by affecting the performance of modules. In this research, we benefited from the article "FACTORS AFFECTING SOLAR POWER PRODUCTION EFFICIENCY" published by Ericson Gordo, Nashat Khalaf and Tyler Strangeowl.

L. Casula, G. D’Amico and G. Masala who are performed an examination on performance estimation of photovoltaic energy production, state that two climatic variables (temperature and wind speed) and the solar radiation play a significant role on the prediction.

Their study demonstrates that form a model on an hourly basis, yields better result, makes the stochastic process more predictable. Based on this assumption, the solar radiation model is formed with a mixture of Kumaraswamy distributions. Then, the temperature model is formed with the following formula:

Looking at the summary of the first model, it can be seen that the day of the week does not have a significant effect on the production rate. When it comes to lag 72, there seems to be a problem in that the production rate highly depends on even the little changes in the regressors, so the addition of the production rates of three days ago can result in a misleading prediction, especially in extreme conditions.

Results¶

After all these iterations of preparing data, manipulating, visualizing and extracting insight, adding and removing regressors, and identifying alternative models, it was observed that the models prepared by dividing by hours worked best. At this stage, we did not attempt to remove any variable from the model from any location, as we think it is a risky approach. For such a decision, we think that it would be useful to examine the production facility geographically and to benefit from the views of scientists. Besides, we think the biggest shortcoming of the model is that it still doesn't catch the unexpectedly large production rate drops.

Conclusions and Future Work¶

As a result, in line with the steps we mentioned above, we tried to predict the next day's production values in a solar energy production plant. For this, the data was examined with time series analysis, the necessary components were added, and a different forecasting model was created for each hour, considering that the production values depend too much on the hour factor (both intiutive and data-driven decision). In order not to be affected by the changes in the clear-sky (capacity) values and the high variation of output values between seasons, only a part of the available data was used for training. The resulting model compared the SARIMA model in terms of WMAPE and it was seen that the hourly models made better predictions. At this point, as we mentioned in the results area, two issues that require further examination are as follows:

1) Some locations may be unrelevant to the production: At this stage, we did not want to exclude any variable in any location from the model. We thought that this should not be just a data-driven decision, but a decision that should be made considering the geographical structure of the region. For this reason, some regressors can be removed from the model by making new studies in this direction. Also, it would be better if these studies are done separately for each different hour model.

2) Unexpected big drops in production rate: For a reason not found in regressors, very large decreases in production value can cause high increases in WMAPE value because they cannot be detected by the model. For this reason, it may be necessary to examine the causes of such sudden drops that may occur in a production facility with a more scientific approach and add new regressors that can catch these drops. Such an approach will also largely solve the bias problem in errors.
